            SELECT
                c.relname,
                CASE
                    WHEN c.relispartition THEN 'p'
                    WHEN c.relkind IN ('m', 'v') THEN 'v'
                    ELSE 't'
                END,
                obj_description(c.oid, 'pg_class')
            FROM pg_catalog.pg_class c
            LEFT JOIN pg_catalog.pg_namespace n ON n.oid = c.relnamespace
            WHERE c.relkind IN ('f', 'm', 'p', 'r', 'v')
                AND n.nspname NOT IN ('pg_catalog', 'pg_toast')
                AND pg_catalog.pg_table_is_visible(c.oid)
        ; args=None; alias=default

                    SUM(CASE WHEN is_succ = FALSE THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) AS failure_count,
                    ROUND(100.0 * SUM(CASE WHEN is_succ = FALSE THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) / COUNT(*), 2) AS failure_rate
                FROM 
                    scrutiny_scrutinyrecord
                GROUP BY 
                    project_id;
            ; args=None; alias=default

            SELECT
                c.relname,
                CASE
                    WHEN c.relispartition THEN 'p'
                    WHEN c.relkind IN ('m', 'v') THEN 'v'
                    ELSE 't'
                END,
                obj_description(c.oid, 'pg_class')
            FROM pg_catalog.pg_class c
            LEFT JOIN pg_catalog.pg_namespace n ON n.oid = c.relnamespace
            WHERE c.relkind IN ('f', 'm', 'p', 'r', 'v')

2024-12-02 11:16:09,914 - DEBUG - (0.015) 
            SELECT
                c.relname,
                CASE
                    WHEN c.relispartition THEN 'p'
                    WHEN c.relkind IN ('m', 'v') THEN 'v'
                    ELSE 't'
                END,
                obj_description(c.oid, 'pg_class')
            FROM pg_catalog.pg_class c
            LEFT JOIN pg_catalog.pg_namespace n ON n.oid = c.relnamespace
            WHERE c.relkind IN ('f', 'm', 'p', 'r', 'v')
                AND n.nspname NOT IN ('pg_catalog', 'pg_toast')
                AND pg_catalog.pg_table_is_visible(c.oid)
        ; args=None; alias=default

2024-12-02 11:38:07,018 - DEBUG - (0.006) 
            SELECT
                c.conname,
                array(
                    SELECT attname
                    FROM unnest(c.conkey) WITH ORDINALITY cols(colid, arridx)
                    JOIN pg_attribute AS ca ON cols.colid = ca.attnum
                    WHERE ca.attrelid = c.conrelid
                    ORDER BY cols.arridx
                ),
                c.contype,
                (SELECT fkc.relname || '.' || fka.attname
                FROM pg_attribute AS fka
                JOIN pg_class AS fkc ON fka.attrelid = fkc.oid
                WHERE fka.attrelid = c.confrelid AND fka.attnum = c.confkey[1]),
                cl.reloptions
            FROM pg_constraint AS c
            JOIN pg_class AS cl ON c.conrelid = cl.oid
            WHERE cl.relname = 'scrutiny_scrutinyrecord' AND pg_catalog.pg_table_is_visible(cl.oid)
        ; args=['scrutiny_scrutinyrecord']; alias=default
2024-12-02 11:38:07,024 - DEBUG - (0.006) 
            SELECT
                indexname,
                array_agg(attname ORDER BY arridx),
                indisunique,
                indisprimary,
                array_agg(ordering ORDER BY arridx),
                amname,
                exprdef,
                s2.attoptions
            FROM (
                SELECT
                    c2.relname as indexname, idx.*, attr.attname, am.amname,
                    CASE
                        WHEN idx.indexprs IS NOT NULL THEN
                            pg_get_indexdef(idx.indexrelid)
                    END AS exprdef,
                    CASE am.amname
                        WHEN 'btree' THEN
                            CASE (option & 1)
                                WHEN 1 THEN 'DESC' ELSE 'ASC'
                            END
                    END as ordering,
                    c2.reloptions as attoptions
                FROM (
                    SELECT *
                    FROM
                        pg_index i,
                        unnest(i.indkey, i.indoption)
                            WITH ORDINALITY koi(key, option, arridx)
                ) idx
                LEFT JOIN pg_class c ON idx.indrelid = c.oid
                LEFT JOIN pg_class c2 ON idx.indexrelid = c2.oid
                LEFT JOIN pg_am am ON c2.relam = am.oid
                LEFT JOIN
                    pg_attribute attr ON attr.attrelid = c.oid AND attr.attnum = idx.key
                WHERE c.relname = 'scrutiny_scrutinyrecord' AND pg_catalog.pg_table_is_visible(c.oid)
            ) s2
            GROUP BY indexname, indisunique, indisprimary, amname, exprdef, attoptions;
        ; args=['btree', 'scrutiny_scrutinyrecord']; alias=default

            SELECT
                c.relname,
                CASE
                    WHEN c.relispartition THEN 'p'
                    WHEN c.relkind IN ('m', 'v') THEN 'v'
                    ELSE 't'
                END,
                obj_description(c.oid, 'pg_class')
            FROM pg_catalog.pg_class c
            LEFT JOIN pg_catalog.pg_namespace n ON n.oid = c.relnamespace
            WHERE c.relkind IN ('f', 'm', 'p', 'r', 'v')
                AND n.nspname NOT IN ('pg_catalog', 'pg_toast')
                AND pg_catalog.pg_table_is_visible(c.oid)
        ; args=None; alias=default

The digitization of land records, for example, has not only reduced the likelihood of disputes but also empowered individuals by providing them with easy access to their property details. Initiatives like these foster transparency, enhance efficiency, and minimize bureaucratic hurdles, demonstrating the department’s commitment to citizen-centric services. Moreover, the Revenue Department plays a crucial role during emergencies, such as natural disasters. Its ability to quickly assess damages and allocate relief funds ensures that affected communities receive timely support. Additionally, the department''s involvement in land acquisition for developmental projects often serves as a bridge between government policy and public benefit, contributing to infrastructure growth, urban planning, and resource allocation. However, despite its many achievements, the Revenue Department also faces notable challenges that cannot be overlooked. One of the primary concerns is the occasional delay in resolving disputes related to land ownership or taxation. These delays often result from systemic inefficiencies or outdated processes that are yet to be fully addressed despite ongoing modernization efforts. In some cases, citizens report inconsistencies in land records or procedural ambiguities that complicate property-related transactions. Such issues can lead to financial strain, legal entanglements, and a loss of trust in the system.

Corruption remains another significant challenge within the Revenue Department. Government departments responsible for roads and buildings play a pivotal role in shaping the physical and functional landscape of communities, contributing significantly to economic development, public safety, and overall quality of life. These departments are tasked with the planning, design, construction, maintenance, and regulation of essential infrastructure, ensuring that it meets the evolving needs of society while adhering to standards of safety, sustainability, and efficiency. The collaborative efforts of engineers, architects, planners, and policymakers within these agencies help to create a network of roads and buildings that facilitate seamless transportation, support civic activities, and provide spaces for residential, commercial, and institutional purposes.
The road management divisions within these departments are responsible for the creation and maintenance of transportation networks that enable mobility and connectivity across urban and rural areas. This includes constructing new roads, highways, and bridges, as well as upgrading and repairing existing infrastructure to ensure safety and durability. Modern technologies such as smart traffic management systems, high-performance materials, and eco-friendly construction techniques are increasingly being employed to enhance the functionality and sustainability of road infrastructure. Departments prioritize the integration of pedestrian pathways, bicycle lanes, and public transportation corridors into road designs to promote multimodal transportation and reduce environmental impact.
Similarly, the building divisions focus on designing and managing the construction of public buildings such as schools, hospitals, government offices, and cultural centers. These spaces are essential for delivering public services and fostering community engagement. Departments oversee everything from architectural design to structural engineering, ensuring that buildings are resilient, energy-efficient, and compliant with local codes and regulations. In recent years, there has been a significant push toward adopting green building practices, including the use of renewable materials, energy-efficient systems, and water-saving technologies, reflecting the government’s commitment to environmental stewardship.
Coordination between road and building divisions is often necessary for comprehensive urban development projects. For instance, the construction of a new hospital may require associated roadworks, such as widening existing roads, improving intersections, or creating new access points to accommodate increased traffic. Similarly, the development of commercial complexes often involves planning for parking facilities, sidewalks, and connectivity to public transit. This integrated approach ensures that both roads and buildings function cohesively to meet the needs of the community.
Another key responsibility of these departments is ensuring public safety. Regular inspections and maintenance activities are conducted to identify and address potential risks, such as potholes on roads, structural weaknesses in bridges, or fire safety issues in buildings. Departments also play a critical role in emergency response and disaster management, quickly mobilizing resources to repair damaged infrastructure and restore services following natural disasters like floods, earthquakes, or hurricanes. Their proactive measures, such as retrofitting bridges to withstand earthquakes or implementing flood-resistant designs in buildings, help to mitigate risks and protect lives.
Public engagement is a growing priority for government departments managing roads and buildings. Citizens are increasingly being involved in the planning process through consultations, public hearings, and participatory design workshops. This inclusive approach not only ensures that projects align with community needs but also fosters trust and transparency between the government and the public. For example, when planning a new roadway or public building, departments often seek feedback on issues such as accessibility, environmental impact, and aesthetic preferences to create outcomes that reflect the values and priorities of the community.

Funding and resource management are critical aspects of the operations of these departments. Road and building projects often require substantial financial investment, sourced from government budgets, public-private partnerships, or grants. Departments must balance competing demands, allocate resources efficiently, and ensure accountability in the use of public funds. Advanced project management tools and techniques are employed to monitor timelines, budgets, and quality standards, minimizing delays and cost overruns.

The adoption of technology is transforming the way government departments manage roads and buildings. Geographic Information Systems (GIS) are used for mapping and planning road networks, while Building Information Modeling (BIM) facilitates efficient design and construction processes for buildings. Drones and sensors enable precise inspections and real-time monitoring, improving maintenance and reducing costs. Smart city initiatives are also gaining momentum, where integrated systems optimize traffic flow, monitor structural health, and enhance energy efficiency in public buildings, paving the way for more responsive and sustainable infrastructure.

Challenges remain, however, as these departments navigate issues such as aging infrastructure, climate change, rapid urbanization, and limited resources. Addressing these challenges requires innovative solutions, cross-sector collaboration, and a long-term vision. Governments are increasingly focusing on resilience and adaptability, prioritizing projects that not only address current demands but also anticipate future needs. For example, the development of roads designed to accommodate electric and autonomous vehicles or the construction of buildings with modular designs that can be reconfigured for different uses highlights the forward-thinking strategies being implemented.

In conclusion, government departments responsible for roads and buildings are essential pillars of modern society, working tirelessly to create infrastructure that supports economic growth, public safety, and community well-being. Through their dedication to innovation, sustainability, and public engagement, these agencies ensure that the foundations of cities and towns are strong, adaptable, and equipped to meet the challenges of the future.             SELECT
                c.relname,
                CASE
                    WHEN c.relispartition THEN 'p'
                    WHEN c.relkind IN ('m', 'v') THEN 'v'
                    ELSE 't'
                END,
                obj_description(c.oid, 'pg_class')
            FROM pg_catalog.pg_class c
            LEFT JOIN pg_catalog.pg_namespace n ON n.oid = c.relnamespace
            WHERE c.relkind IN ('f', 'm', 'p', 'r', 'v')
                AND n.nspname NOT IN ('pg_catalog', 'pg_toast')
                AND pg_catalog.pg_table_is_visible(c.oid)
        ; args=None; alias=default

2024-12-07 14:15:53,066 - DEBUG - (0.009) 
            SELECT
                c.relname,
                CASE
                    WHEN c.relispartition THEN 'p'
                    WHEN c.relkind IN ('m', 'v') THEN 'v'
                    ELSE 't'
                END,
                obj_description(c.oid, 'pg_class')
            FROM pg_catalog.pg_class c
            LEFT JOIN pg_catalog.pg_namespace n ON n.oid = c.relnamespace
            WHERE c.relkind IN ('f', 'm', 'p', 'r', 'v')
                AND n.nspname NOT IN ('pg_catalog', 'pg_toast')
                AND pg_catalog.pg_table_is_visible(c.oid)
        ; args=None; alias=default

            SELECT
                c.conname,
                array(
                    SELECT attname
                    FROM unnest(c.conkey) WITH ORDINALITY cols(colid, arridx)
                    JOIN pg_attribute AS ca ON cols.colid = ca.attnum
                    WHERE ca.attrelid = c.conrelid
                    ORDER BY cols.arridx
                ),
                c.contype,
                (SELECT fkc.relname || '.' || fka.attname
                FROM pg_attribute AS fka
                JOIN pg_class AS fkc ON fka.attrelid = fkc.oid
                WHERE fka.attrelid = c.confrelid AND fka.attnum = c.confkey[1]),
                cl.reloptions
            FROM pg_constraint AS c
            JOIN pg_class AS cl ON c.conrelid = cl.oid
            WHERE cl.relname = 'scrutiny_scrutinyrecord' AND pg_catalog.pg_table_is_visible(cl.oid)
        ; args=['scrutiny_scrutinyrecord']; alias=default
2024-12-07 14:15:59,349 - DEBUG - (0.039) 
            SELECT
                indexname,
                array_agg(attname ORDER BY arridx),
                indisunique,
                indisprimary,
                array_agg(ordering ORDER BY arridx),
                amname,
                exprdef,
                s2.attoptions
            FROM (
                SELECT
                    c2.relname as indexname, idx.*, attr.attname, am.amname,
                    CASE
                        WHEN idx.indexprs IS NOT NULL THEN
                            pg_get_indexdef(idx.indexrelid)
                    END AS exprdef,
                    CASE am.amname
                        WHEN 'btree' THEN
                            CASE (option & 1)
                                WHEN 1 THEN 'DESC' ELSE 'ASC'
                            END
                    END as ordering,
                    c2.reloptions as attoptions
                FROM (
                    SELECT *
                    FROM
                        pg_index i,
                        unnest(i.indkey, i.indoption)
                            WITH ORDINALITY koi(key, option, arridx)
                ) idx
                LEFT JOIN pg_class c ON idx.indrelid = c.oid
                LEFT JOIN pg_class c2 ON idx.indexrelid = c2.oid
                LEFT JOIN pg_am am ON c2.relam = am.oid
                LEFT JOIN
                    pg_attribute attr ON attr.attrelid = c.oid AND attr.attnum = idx.key
                WHERE c.relname = 'scrutiny_scrutinyrecord' AND pg_catalog.pg_table_is_visible(c.oid)
            ) s2
            GROUP BY indexname, indisunique, indisprimary, amname, exprdef, attoptions;
        ; args=['btree', 'scrutiny_scrutinyrecord']; alias=default

            SELECT
                c.relname,
                CASE
                    WHEN c.relispartition THEN 'p'
                    WHEN c.relkind IN ('m', 'v') THEN 'v'
                    ELSE 't'
                END,
                obj_description(c.oid, 'pg_class')
            FROM pg_catalog.pg_class c
            LEFT JOIN pg_catalog.pg_namespace n ON n.oid = c.relnamespace
            WHERE c.relkind IN ('f', 'm', 'p', 'r', 'v')
                AND n.nspname NOT IN ('pg_catalog', 'pg_toast')
                AND pg_catalog.pg_table_is_visible(c.oid)
        ; args=None; alias=default

                c.relname,
                CASE
                    WHEN c.relispartition THEN 'p'
                    WHEN c.relkind IN ('m', 'v') THEN 'v'
                    ELSE 't'
                END,
                obj_description(c.oid, 'pg_class')
            FROM pg_catalog.pg_class c
            LEFT JOIN pg_catalog.pg_namespace n ON n.oid = c.relnamespace
            WHERE c.relkind IN ('f', 'm', 'p', 'r', 'v')
